section.p:
We shall need first of all two special cases of more general formulas which are frequently applied in succeeding pages. Let E_{34} be a straight-line segment of variable length which moves so that its end-points describe simultaneously the two curves C and D shown in , and let the equations of these curves in parametric form be

   (C) \quad x \amp=x_3(t), y=y_3(t), 
   (D) \quad x \amp=x_4(t), y=y_4(t). 

The length
 I=\sqrt{\left(x_{4}-x_{3}\right)^{2}+\left(y_{4}-y_{3}\right)^{2}}  
of the segment E_{34} has the differential 
dI=\frac{\left(x_{4}-x_{3}\right)\left(d x_{4}-d x_{3}\right)+\left(y_{4}-y_{3}\right)\left(d y_{4}-d y_{3}\right)}{\sqrt{\left(x_{4}-x_{3}\right)^{2}+\left(y_{4}-y_{3}\right)^{2}}}

When the notation

  p=\frac{y_4-y_3}{x_4-x_3}

is used to denote the slope of the line E_{34} this result may be expressed in the more convenient formula of the following theorem:

statement.p:
If a straight-line segment E_{34} moves so that its end-points 3 and 4 describe simultaneously two curves C and D, as shown in , then the length I of E_{34} has the differential

  dI\left(E_{34}\right)=\left.\frac{dx+p\,dy}{\sqrt{1+p^{2}}}\right|^4_{3}

where the vertical bar indicates that the value of the preceding expression at the point 3 is to be subtracted from its value at the point 4. In this formula the differentials dx, dy at the points 3 and 4 are those belonging to C and D, while p is the slope of the segment E_{34}.
